"""hyper — the operator's interface to hypercore.

One file, stdlib only, keyboard only.  Every frame is read fresh from
disk: intent.md (the system), queue.md (decision cards), words.md (the
exchanges), work.md (standing work).  Every move the operator makes
lands on disk and is committed in their name before the screen redraws.
The screen re-reads disk on a one-second tick, so what lands shows up
on its own — no restart anywhere.

    ./hyper

Views    queue (home) . decision card . work-decision card .
         acceptance card . exchange . work . document . log
Decide   a approve . c cut . e explain (words optional); the verbs are
         the same on every card — on a standing-work decision approve
         lands on the card as if spoken, y confirms, and the machine
         executes it; the card's options wear numbers, 1–9 picks one,
         y confirms, and the option's own words land in the operator's
         name; a decisive word (approve, cut, a pick) settles the card
         on the spot — the entry leaves work.md in the same commit,
         nothing is left for the operator to do; s speaks in the
         operator's own words
Accept   a approve then y on an acceptance card — confirmed like every
         other release; s speaks reservations
Speak    s anywhere — words land verbatim, the place travels with them,
         and the machine is summoned to work while you watch
Graphs   hypercore's execution graphs are its children and sit under
         its line, never beside it — unfold hypercore to reach them
         below its work entries; enter on a graph line opens its nodes
         (<name>/graph.md, read live), headed by the parent its root
         names (of: hypercore), d opens its documents; open graphs live
         under work/, folded ones under archive/ — the fold moves the
         folder; folded graphs stay listed, marked folded
Machine  the record calling is the summons — at launch, a behind record
         or waiting words start the machine without m, and words landing
         mid-answer summon it once more when the run ends; m stays as
         the manual retry after a failed or partial run.  a bare true-up
         (no words waiting) goes to the mini, the small machine in the
         mini file: it commits what is on disk and never finishes or
         corrects; anything it leaves, and every word, goes to the full
         machine
Move     arrows . left/right across cards (j previous, k next) . up/down
         within the screen . enter open . esc back . q quit
"""

